e assembled histories and ethnographies span three continents and use the lived experiences of physicians and patients, consumers and providers, and marketers and regulators to reveal the tensions between universal claims of therapeutic knowledge and the actual ways these claims have been used and understood in specific sites, from postwar West Germany pharmacies to twenty-first century Nigerian street markets. By asking us to rethink a story we thought we knew, Therapeutic Revolutions offers invaluable insights to historians, anthropologists, and social scientists of medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPharmaceutical industryxSocial aspects. 0aTherapeuticsxSocial aspects. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  abiomedicine.  aconsumer history.  ahistory of medicine.  ahistory of science.  amedical anthropology.  amodern medicine.  apharmaceutical industry.  aprescription drugs.  atherapeutic revolution.  atwentieth century history.1 aBasilico, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonah, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCondrau, Flurin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCondrau, Flurin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFarmer, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Jeremy A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Jeremy A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHenckes, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKehr, Janina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKessel, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4h